      Elon merger stuff (not Twitter)
   =20
 =20
Elon Musk is becoming a leading figure in American mergers and acquisitions=
. This week he agreed to  buy Twitter Inc.=C2=A0in what will probably be th=
e largest leveraged buyout ever done by a guy in his personal account.=C2=
=A0In 2018 he spent a week pretending he was going to take Tesla Inc. priva=
te, in what was perhaps the largest pretend leveraged buyout ever done by a=
 public-company chief executive officer, though I am not sure precisely how=
 one would measure that. And yesterday  he won an important Delaware Chance=
ry Court case over his 2016 purchase of SolarCity Corp. Future law students=
 will take courses in Elon Musk M&A,=C2=A0just like future finance students=
 will take courses in the  Elon Markets Hypothesis. Everywhere he goes, he =
creates=C2=A0issues.The SolarCity deal was=C2=A0not=C2=A0a leveraged buyout=
; Musk did not buy it for his personal account. Instead, Tesla bought it, f=
or about $2.6 billion of stock. That=E2=80=99s the problem. SolarCity was a=
 public solar company; Musk was the chairman of its board of directors and =
its largest shareholder, and it had been founded by his cousins. Tesla is=
=C2=A0a public company that makes electric cars (and now owns SolarCity); M=
usk was at the time its chairman and chief executive officer and owned 22% =
of its stock. (He is now its =E2=80=9CTechnoking=E2=80=9D and owns somewhat=
 less of the stock.) Musk decided that Tesla should buy SolarCity. Tesla, a=
 company he ran, then bought SolarCity, a company that he owned a lot of.=
=C2=A0This raises an obvious conflict of interest, so some Tesla shareholde=
rs sued. From Vice Chancellor Joseph Slights=E2=80=99s opinion yesterday:Ac=
cording to the plaintiffs, as Tesla=E2=80=99s controlling stockholder, Elon=
 caused Tesla=E2=80=99s servile Board to approve the Acquisition of an inso=
lvent SolarCity at a patently unfair price, following a highly flawed proce=
ss, in order to bail out his (and other family members=E2=80=99) foundering=
 investment in SolarCity. This, say the plaintiffs, was a clear breach of E=
lon=E2=80=99s fiduciary duty of loyalty.=C2=A0The competing theory is that =
Musk had a =E2=80=9CMaster Plan=E2=80=9D for Tesla, that the Master Plan wa=
s not about making electric cars but about how to =E2=80=9Caccelerate the w=
orld=E2=80=99s transition to sustainable energy,=E2=80=9D that SolarCity fi=
t perfectly into this plan, that Musk wanted Tesla to buy SolarCity because=
 that was the right strategic decision for Tesla, and that the price Tesla =
paid was fair.These are hard theories to adjudicate. Elon Musk is very smar=
t and Tesla=E2=80=99s stock has gone up a lot, so it seems silly to assume =
that he did=C2=A0not=C2=A0have a genuine strategic vision for Tesla or that=
 SolarCity wasn=E2=80=99t part of it. On the other hand, SolarCity absolute=
ly was founded by his cousins and he absolutely did own a lot of its stock,=
 so it seems silly to say that he wasn=E2=80=99t conflicted in telling Tesl=
a to buy SolarCity.Broadly speaking there are two ways to address this prob=
lem. One is that each board of directors =E2=80=94=C2=A0at Tesla and SolarC=
ity =E2=80=94=C2=A0can set up a special committee of independent directors =
to review the transaction and decide if it is fair for their companies, fre=
e from any influence from Musk or other conflicted directors, and then put =
in place other safeguards =E2=80=94=C2=A0market checks, fairness opinions, =
majority-of-the-minority shareholder votes, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0to make sur=
e that the deal both looks and is fair.The other way to address the problem=
 is to punt it to a judge. Aggrieved shareholders can sue and say =E2=80=9C=
Tesla should not have bought SolarCity, and certainly should not have paid =
$2.6 billion, so Elon Musk should have to pay shareholders back,=E2=80=9D a=
nd they can make their case for why SolarCity was a bad strategic fit and n=
ot worth $2.6 billion. And Musk can make his case for why it was a good str=
ategic fit and worth way more than $2.6 billion.[1] And the judge can liste=
n to both sides and decide who is right.The first approach is obviously pre=
ferable, and it is what basically every public company, in situations like =
this, aims for. Oversimplifying mightily,[2] the way Delaware M&A law gener=
ally works is that if you get the process stuff right =E2=80=94=C2=A0if you=
 have the right combination of independent special committees and ratifying=
 shareholder votes and careful free unconflicted negotiations =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0the court will not second-guess the deal=E2=80=99s price or strategic lo=
gic; a properly done deal will be subject to deferential =E2=80=9Cbusiness =
judgment=E2=80=9D review. If you get the process stuff wrong, you get =E2=
=80=9Centire fairness=E2=80=9D review, meaning that the court gets to decid=
e if the price was fair.The right way to do the process is to set up a spec=
ial committee of Tesla directors with no ties of personal loyalty to Musk, =
let them meet regularly without the conflicted board members (like Musk, or=
 his brother Kimbal), give them free rein to hire financial and legal advis=
ers and negotiate the deal, and give them an=C2=A0absolute right to reject =
a deal with no repercussions. If they accept a deal under those conditions,=
 it=E2=80=99s probably=C2=A0fair. It is a little hard to imagine this worki=
ng with Elon Musk! You have to kick him out of his own board meetings, and =
you have to keep open the possibility of saying no to something he really w=
ants.Still, the Tesla board did okay. Musk proposed buying SolarCity severa=
l times, and the board said no a few times because Tesla had other things o=
n its plate. Eventually it agreed to consider a deal and hired financial an=
d legal advisers (Evercore and Wachtell, Lipton, Rosen & Katz[3]) to vet it=
; it also=C2=A0sort of=C2=A0kicked Musk out of the meetings:Once the Tesla =
Board decided it would pursue an acquisition of SolarCity, following discus=
sions with counsel, it was determined that Elon and [Tesla and SolarCity di=
rector Antonio] Gracias should be recused from any vote relating to the tra=
nsaction given, among other conflicts, their roles on the SolarCity Board.=
=C2=A0But the Tesla Board believed that Elon and Gracias=E2=80=99 perspecti=
ves regarding the solar industry and SolarCity,=C2=A0in particular, would b=
e helpful, so it was agreed that the two could participate in certain high-=
level strategic discussions regarding the Acquisition.Evercore presented it=
s analysis of=C2=A0the potential deal to the board and recommended a price =
of roughly $25 to $27 per share; Musk, who=C2=A0of course was at this meeti=
ng, proposed $28.50. The board approved an initial offer at a range between=
 those prices, and despite Musk=E2=80=99s request that Tesla also give Sola=
rCity a bridge loan until the deal closed =E2=80=94=C2=A0SolarCity=E2=80=99=
s finances were in rough shape =E2=80=94=C2=A0the board said no.Then they n=
egotiated a deal, and =E2=80=9CEvercore=E2=80=99s 10-member team spent thou=
sands of hours reviewing SolarCity=E2=80=99s financial condition, conductin=
g valuation analyses and negotiating with Lazard,=E2=80=9D SolarCity=E2=80=
=99s bankers. With SolarCity=C2=A0running out of cash, =E2=80=9CElon arrang=
ed daily meetings with the Evercore team to push along the pace of due dili=
gence=E2=80=9D and hurry up the deal. =E2=80=9CGiven the information discov=
ered in diligence, Evercore decided to recommend that Tesla lower its offer=
,=E2=80=9D and presented this recommendation at a board meeting that=C2=A0o=
f course Musk attended. (He agreed to lower the price.) Eventually they sig=
ned a deal, and Evercore gave a fairness opinion saying that the price was =
fair to Tesla. (Meanwhile=C2=A0SolarCity=E2=80=99s short-term cash needs we=
re met by Musk and his cousins buying $100 million of SolarCity bonds in th=
eir personal accounts.) Then Tesla went out and got a shareholder vote; the=
 board required that a majority of non-Musk shareholders vote for the deal,=
 and about 85% of them did.That process is, you know, okay. Better to have =
a special committee, better not to have Musk back-channeling with the banke=
rs and attending every important board=C2=A0meeting that he was supposedly =
recused from. Vice Chancellor Slights gives it like a B-:The process employ=
ed by the Tesla Board to negotiate and ultimately recommend the Acquisition=
 was far from perfect. Elon was more involved in the process than a conflic=
ted fiduciary should be. And conflicts among other Tesla Board members were=
 not completely neutralized. With that said, the Tesla Board meaningfully v=
etted the Acquisition, and Elon did not stand in its way.That seems right. =
Musk was involved, but the board seems to have taken its job seriously and =
tried to negotiate a fair deal.=C2=A0Still, the judge more or less gives up=
 on answering the question of whether this process was=C2=A0enough, and ins=
tead decides to =E2=80=9Cskip to entire fairness.=E2=80=9D[4] Assuming that=
 the process was=C2=A0not=C2=A0good enough, then the way shareholders are p=
rotected from conflicts of interest is by going to court and persuading a j=
udge that Tesla should not have bought SolarCity, or that it overpaid.=C2=
=A0But he was not persuaded:The preponderance of the evidence reveals that =
Tesla paid a fair price=E2=80=94SolarCity was, at a minimum, worth what Tes=
la paid for it, and the Acquisition otherwise was highly beneficial to Tesl=
a. Indeed, the Acquisition marked a vital step forward for a company that h=
ad for years made clear to the market=C2=A0and its stockholders that it int=
ended to expand from an electric car manufacturer to an alternative energy =
company. The Court=E2=80=99s verdict, therefore, is for the defense.He goes=
 through the arguments =E2=80=94=C2=A0about SolarCity=E2=80=99s market valu=
ation, its cash flows, its alleged insolvency, potential synergies, the val=
ue of Evercore=E2=80=99s fairness opinion, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0but ultimate=
ly he seems most persuaded by a general sense=C2=A0that Elon Musk is a busi=
ness genius and Tesla=E2=80=99s stock has gone up a ton since this deal:Whi=
le the synergistic effects of the Acquisition are still unfolding, the astr=
onomic rise in Tesla=E2=80=99s stock price post-Acquisition is noteworthy. =
Although the relevant inquiry in an entire fairness analysis is whether the=
 acquisition target was worth the price paid when the deal was consummated,=
 hindsight suggests that Elon is right when he asserts that, once valued as=
 a car company, Tesla=C2=A0is now valued as =E2=80=9Ca first-of-its-kind, v=
ertically integrated clean energy company.=E2=80=9DWhether the Acquisition =
played a large or small part in Tesla=E2=80=99s impressive growth is not cl=
ear, but there can be no doubt that the combination with SolarCity has allo=
wed Tesla to become what it has for years told the market and its stockhold=
ers it strives to be=E2=80=93=E2=80=93an agent of change that will =E2=80=
=9Caccelerate the world=E2=80=99s transition to sustainable energy=E2=80=9D=
 by =E2=80=9Chelp[ing] to expedite the move from a mine-and-burn hydrocarbo=
n economy towards a solar electric economy.=E2=80=9DBut he also says: =E2=
=80=9CI=C2=A0cannot help but observe that Elon (and the rest of the Tesla B=
oard members) likely could have avoided this expensive and time-consuming l=
itigation had they just adopted more objectively evident procedural protect=
ions.=E2=80=9DThose are the two sides of Elon Musk, aren=E2=80=99t they? On=
 the one hand he infuriatingly refuses to comply with the basic expectation=
s of law and society; on the other hand Tesla=E2=80=99s stock keeps going u=
p. =E2=80=9CElon Musk is a bullshitter who delivers,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Benedict=
 Evans says. He did a deal that was rotten with conflicts of interest, and =
while he=C2=A0could=C2=A0have followed the proper procedures to do the deal=
 right, he=C2=A0didn=E2=80=99t, because he is too impetuous and doesn=E2=80=
=99t really believe in rules or social norms. But also the deal worked out =
great and confirmed his reputation as a business genius. And so the Delawar=
e judge spends some time criticizing him for doing the deal wrong, but his =
heart isn=E2=80=99t in it. Musk is too much of a lovable business scamp for=
 any judge to stay mad at him. He does all the wrong things but they keep w=
orking out=C2=A0right.=20
