Twitter Inc. signed a somewhat disappointing  merger agreement with Elon Mu=
sk on Monday and released its first-quarter earnings today.=C2=A0Just knowi=
ng those two facts, you could have predicted that the earnings would also b=
e disappointing, but not=C2=A0too=C2=A0disappointing. Actual results for th=
e quarter were $1.2 billion of revenue, $0.61 of earnings per share=C2=A0un=
der generally accepted accounting principles and $0.90 of=C2=A0non-GAAP adj=
usted earnings per share, compared to estimates of $1.23 billion, negative =
$0.18 and $0.03, respectively. So a beat on earnings but a miss on revenue.=
=C2=A0Daily active users were up 16% to 229 million, a slight beat. All a b=
it better than I would have expected? The basic model here is:=09When it si=
gned the merger agreement on Monday, Twitter=E2=80=99s board presumably kne=
w what the earnings release would say, at least in general terms, but the p=
ublic did not.=09Musk=C2=A0also might not have known what the earnings rele=
ase would say, because he declined to do any nonpublic due diligence on Twi=
tter, for reasons of speed and weirdness.[5]=09If the earnings were great, =
and the board knew that, it would not have accepted $54.20 per share. It wo=
uld have told its bankers about its great earnings, and its prospects for g=
reat future earnings, and they would have built a model showing that Twitte=
r was worth much more than $54.20, and the board would have told Musk to ge=
t lost. That is very much   not what happened.=09If the earnings were catas=
trophic, the board would have been psyched to get $54.20 per share, but als=
o very nervous? Like the merger agreement   basically says =E2=80=9Cif Twit=
ter=E2=80=99s=C2=A0earnings are terrible, Musk still can=E2=80=99t walk awa=
y,=E2=80=9D but it is not fun to sign a merger on Monday and then tell the =
buyer on Thursday =E2=80=9Coh by the way our business fell apart last quart=
er, hope that=E2=80=99s okay.=E2=80=9D Possibly the best choice! But unsett=
ling.=09If the earnings were meh, then you sign the deal and three days lat=
er everyone gets to say =E2=80=9Coh yeah this is why they sold the company,=
 fine.=E2=80=9DAmusingly, Twitter also announced that its prior public disc=
losures about daily active users were wrong:In March of 2019, we launched a=
 feature that allowed people to link multiple separate accounts together in=
 order to conveniently switch between accounts. An error was made at that t=
ime, such that actions taken via the primary account resulted in all linked=
 accounts being counted as mDAU. This resulted in an overstatement of mDAU =
from Q1=E2=80=9919 through Q4=E2=80=9921.=C2=A0Not=C2=A0that=C2=A0wrong =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0off by 1% or so =E2=80=94=C2=A0but wrong. The merger agreement =
that Twitter signed with Musk contains a representation (Section 4.6(a)) th=
at =E2=80=9Cnone of the Company SEC Documents =E2=80=A6 contained any untru=
e statement of a material fact.=E2=80=9D That representation was =E2=80=A6=
=C2=A0maybe not true? If you were Twitter=E2=80=99s lawyer, you would be a =
little nervous writing in the contract that all of the SEC documents were a=
ccurate, when you knew that some of them were not.It might be worth explain=
ing briefly why they did that and why it is fine:=09Practically speaking th=
e most important point is that, even if this representation was wrong, Musk=
 still can=E2=80=99t walk away from the deal. He can only walk away if (1) =
the company=E2=80=99s representations are wrong and (2) the wrongness would=
 have a =E2=80=9CMaterial Adverse Effect=E2=80=9D on the company. (Section =
7.2(b) of the merger agreement.)=C2=A0If Twitter had announced today =E2=80=
=9Cso uh we said that we had 216.6 million daily active users in the fourth=
 quarter of 2021, but actually we had zero,=E2=80=9D that would likely be a=
n MAE and Musk could walk away. But the correct number was 214.7 million an=
d that is just not material enough.=C2=A0=09Also important, though, is the =
fact that the publicly filed merger agreement comes with another document t=
hat is=C2=A0not=C2=A0filed. This is called the =E2=80=9CCompany Disclosure =
Letter,=E2=80=9D and it basically lists all of the exceptions to the merger=
 agreement.[6] So Section 4.6(a) of the agreement says =E2=80=9Call of our =
SEC filings are fine,=E2=80=9D and Section 4.6(a) of the disclosure letter =
says =E2=80=9Cexcept for the following mistakes:=E2=80=9D and, presumably, =
lists this active-user error. (Assuming they had caught it by last weekend.=
) The disclosure letter is not filed publicly, but Musk and his lawyers get=
 to read it before he signs the merger agreement. Given that Musk declined =
to do nonpublic due diligence on Twitter, I am not sure how detailed the di=
sclosure letter was; he might not have wanted to get any material nonpublic=
 information in the disclosure letter. But I am pretty sure that, if Twitte=
r=E2=80=99s lawyers knew about this active-user mistake, they would have pu=
shed hard to disclose it to Musk. You don=E2=80=99t want to give him any ex=
cuses.Elsewhere in Musk=E2=80=99s Twitter deal, one fun theory=C2=A0is that=
 Musk=E2=80=99s wealth is largely tied up in Tesla Inc. stock, which trades=
 at a huge multiple of earnings due to his meme-y comic-book-character pers=
ona, and he is trying to take profits and diversify that wealth by buying o=
ther stuff in a way that feels consistent with that persona and does not hu=
rt Tesla=E2=80=99s multiple. Pseudonymous finance Twitter personality =E2=
=80=9CSquarely Rooted=E2=80=9D puts this theory well:You need a way to turn=
 even a very large chunk of your very large pile of temporarily-ultra-valua=
ble stonk into something else uncorrelated to the price of the stonk withou=
t so violently puncturing that bubble, via shaking ape confidence, that the=
