any that I would just take the public-relations hit and do it. (Musk=C2=A0d=
id=C2=A0manage to  sell a ton of Tesla stock last year, =E2=80=9Cin charact=
er,=E2=80=9D by  doing a Twitter poll about it; he could have put the proce=
eds into index funds.)=C2=A0But I am not Elon Musk so who knows.=C2=A0Anoth=
er point. I and others have sometimes  discussed Twitter=E2=80=99s proposed=
 debt load under Musk =E2=80=94 $13 billion of bank loans and bonds, with a=
n interest expense of close to $1 billion a year =E2=80=94=C2=A0in comparis=
on to its operating cash flow. Basically the debt service cost of Musk Twit=
ter will be very high relative to it cash flow. But this actually understat=
es the problem,=C2=A0because public Twitter=E2=80=99s employees are paid pa=
rtly in stock, and Musk Twitter would probably have to pay them more in cas=
h.[7]=C2=A0Byrne Hobart notes:The Twitter acquisition makes one other point=
, though: it's a good demonstration that stock-based compensation is a real=
 expense. Twitter's most senior engineers get more than half of their compe=
nsation in the form of equity, and probably don't design their lifestyle ar=
ound the assumption that it will be forever illiquid. So Twitter will need =
to do some combination of paying higher cash compensation and regularly buy=
ing back employee stock, either of which would represent a cash cost roughl=
