ed to enter into the consent decree,=E2=80=9D U.S. District Judge Lewis Lim=
an said in his written opinion. The Tesla CEO =E2=80=9Ccannot now seek to r=
etract the agreement=E2=80=9D by =E2=80=9Csimply bemoaning that he felt lik=
e he had to agree to it at the time=E2=80=9D and now =E2=80=9Cwishes that h=
e had not,=E2=80=9D Liman said.This is completely=C2=A0correct. Musk did a =
lil=E2=80=99 bit of securities fraud in 2018  by tweeting that he had =E2=
=80=9Cfunding secured=E2=80=9D for a Tesla buyout when he just absolutely  =
did not.=C2=A0The SEC  sued him, and he  settled with the SEC for a fine an=
d an agreement to have a lawyer review all of his tweets that might be mate=
rial to Tesla.=C2=A0That lawyer presumably has sterling credentials and the=
 absolute worst job in American law.=C2=A0Musk has gotten bored with all of=
 this and decided that actually, when he said he had =E2=80=9Cfunding secur=
ed=E2=80=9D for that buyout, he did. (He just=C2=A0absolutely did not.) So =
he went to court and said, in effect, =E2=80=9Cactually I should not have s=
ettled, can we forget about the whole thing, particularly the part where so=
me long-suffering securities lawyer is theoretically=C2=A0in charge of revi=
ewing my tweets?=E2=80=9D And the judge said no. The judge was obviously go=
ing to say no. This is dumb.That said, Musk is going to continue to tweet m=
aterial things about Tesla without running them by that poor lawyer, and th=
e SEC is going to continue to be mad about it, and nobody is going to throw=
 him in jail for it. That would also be dumb. He is still subject to the se=
ttlement, which means that he still has to have a lawyer review his tweets,=
 except that he doesn=E2=80=99t.  This is called =E2=80=9Clegal realism.=E2=
=80=9DBy the way,  I keep saying this, but when Musk was buying Twitter sto=
ck he was required to disclose his ownership within 10 days after he reache=
d 5% of the stock. He did not do that.=C2=A0He waited a few extra days and =
bought more stock while he waited, saving himself something like $140 milli=
on. Then, when he did disclose his stake, he used a Schedule 13G representi=
ng that he was a passive investor with no plans for a change of control, ev=
en though he proposed to buy the company nine days later, saying that it wa=
