This is the question that  I asked yesterday about Bill Hwang, who was arre=
sted for alleged=C2=A0market manipulation in connection with the rise and f=
all of his briefly gigantic family office, Archegos Capital Management. I d=
id not have a great answer! Some readers had some suggestions, though, whic=
h I=E2=80=99d like to discuss.The basic story of Archegos is that it borrow=
ed money to buy tons of shares of about 10 stocks, the stocks went up becau=
se it was buying them, it used its profits to borrow more money to buy more=
 shares, the stocks kept going up, etc., until Archegos owned like half of =
the float of many of these stocks at inflated prices. And then something we=
nt slightly wrong, Archegos got margin calls that it couldn=E2=80=99t meet =
because every penny was tied up in these inflated stocks, its brokers dumpe=
d the stocks, the prices collapsed, there were more margin calls and more l=
iquidations, and eventually Archegos=E2=80=99s portfolio went to zero and i=
ts banks lost billions of dollars.Why would he=C2=A0do this?=C2=A0The theor=
y of the Department of Justice and the Securities and Exchange Commission i=
s that Hwang was doing market manipulation, that he bought as much as he co=
uld of these stocks to make them go up. This theory might well be true, but=
 it is very annoying, because this is not a way to make money. It is a way =
to have large paper gains, sure, but in the SEC=E2=80=99s and DOJ=E2=80=99s=
 telling he plowed every cent of those gains back into pushing the stocks u=
p more, which can only end the way it did. Bill Hwang is a smart guy and an=
 experienced hedge fund manager. Perhaps he concocted a scheme to put as mu=
ch money as possible onto a pile and incinerate it all, but that is a dumb =
scheme.My alternative theory was=C2=A0that Hwang could extracted some of hi=
s billions of dollar in profits =E2=80=94 by calling=C2=A0the banks up and =
saying =E2=80=9Chey I see I have some profits in this account, could you wi=
re them to me?=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0and then buried them in his backyard=
.=C2=A0Archegos=C2=A0went to zero, but if Hwang extracted some money from A=
rchegos and put it beyond the reach of margin calls=C2=A0before=C2=A0it wen=
t to zero, then he could be doing pretty well. (Except for being arrested.)=
I said yesterday that this theory =E2=80=9Cseems ruled out=E2=80=9D by the =
indictment, since at the end Archegos allegedly poured every remaining cent=
 into a doomed effort to=C2=A0prop up the prices of its stocks, rather than=
 doing the sensible thing of pouring every remaining cent into giant bags o=
f money and hiding them somewhere. But some readers pushed back on that, I =
think correctly, and=C2=A0it is possible that Hwang plowed=C2=A0most=C2=A0o=
f his gains back into Archegos (and incinerated them) while taking some mon=
ey out of Archegos=C2=A0along the way. The fact that Hwang=E2=80=99s  bail =
was set at $100 million and he met it =E2=80=94=C2=A0though technically he =
only put up $5 million of cash =E2=80=94=C2=A0suggests that, you know, he k=
ept=C2=A0some=C2=A0money. A strategy of =E2=80=9Cmanipulate stocks up, make=
 billions of paper profits, take out a few million for yourself and plow th=
e rest back into more manipulation until you lose it all=E2=80=9D still see=
ms crazy but I guess it=E2=80=99s possible.Another theory that several read=
ers proposed is that he might have had some sort of ally, that by allegedly=
 manipulating these stocks up he made profits for other traders even though=
 it eventually ended in disaster for him. (And maybe the other traders prom=
ised to take care of him, or he just wanted them to be happy, etc.) I don=
=E2=80=99t really buy this, not only because there is no evidence for it bu=
t also=C2=A0because he owned 50% or more of the available shares of several=
 of the stocks he allegedly manipulated: Nobody could have made as much mon=
ey on his trades as he ultimately lost.=C2=A0A third theory, the most appea=
ling one, is that he was working on a short squeeze. His huge long position=
s were mostly in companies that were heavily shorted, he drove up their sto=
cks, and all of this was happening around the same time as the meme-stock c=
raze and its focus on squeezing short sellers. If the stock prices got high=
 enough, the short sellers might be forced to close out their positions by =
buying the stocks at inflated prices, and then Hwang could have sold to the=
m at those inflated prices and gotten out of his trade at an enormous profi=
t.The model here is an insane game of leveraged chicken: Bill Hwang bets on=
 the stock using billions of dollars of borrowed money, short sellers bet a=
gainst it using billions of dollars of borrowed stock, their game comes to =
dominate trading in the stock, and whoever=E2=80=99s=C2=A0lenders=C2=A0blin=
k first loses.There is=C2=A0some=C2=A0support for this theory: Hwang=E2=80=
=99s stocks=C2=A0were=C2=A0heavily shorted, and in fact short sellers  thou=
ght that=E2=80=99s what he was up to:Short seller Carson Block, famous for =
his bearish bets against Chinese companies, said in a May 2021 interview th=
at he hoped the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission would look into the=
 trading in GSX. He questioned whether Archegos and others were trying to s=
queeze such positions.=E2=80=9CJust can=E2=80=99t see that these guys went =
long GSX on such large size because they believed the fundamentals were so =
good,=E2=80=9D he said.Still I am skeptical. For one thing, again, his posi=
tions in these stocks were so huge that it is hard to believe he could have=
 gotten out just by selling to capitulating short sellers. Also he was doin=
g this for months, and the stocks went up a lot as he bought; at some point=
 you have to either say =E2=80=9Caha, the shorts have capitulated=E2=80=9D =
and take your profits,=C2=A0or say =E2=80=9Cwell, they=E2=80=99re not going=
 to capitulate=E2=80=9D and stop.Also I assume that the SEC and DOJ=C2=A0di=
d=C2=A0look into this theory, and that if they had found any evidence that =
Hwang was trying to do a short squeeze, they would have cited it. The SEC v=
ery much thinks that a short squeeze is a form of market manipulation =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0see my all-time favorite=C2=A0SEC enforcement action, against P=
hil Falcone for squeezing the MAAX Holdings Inc. bonds =E2=80=94=C2=A0and i=
t even touches briefly on the idea in the complaint against Hwang. (=E2=80=
=9CHwang=E2=80=99s goal, executed by Tomita, was to induce other traders, s=
uch as short sellers or other market participants, to observe active tradin=
g in and upward price movement of the share prices of certain issuers and, =
as a result, purchase those issuers=E2=80=99 securities during the day.=E2=
=80=9D) But there is no serious suggestion that he was focused on squeezing=
 short sellers, or that he was holding out for some expected capitulation b=
y the shorts. And the SEC and DOJ don=E2=80=99t cite any texts or emails or=
 chats in which he talks about squeezing the shorts, which is uncharacteris=
tic; usually people who want to squeeze shorts feel self-righteous and=C2=
=A0love=C2=A0to talk about it.
 =20
   =20
      People! Are! Worried! About! Bond! Market! Liquidity!
   =20
 =20
It=E2=80=99s back!Wall Street dealers are increasingly reluctant to trade c=
orporate bonds that they can=E2=80=99t immediately offload, and their hesit=
ance has contributed to sharp moves in prices this year.=C2=A0Banks=E2=80=
=99 reticence to buy company debt from investors is showing up in inventory=
 data, which tallies the securities that firms hold on their books rather t=
han sell quickly. Dealer inventories of high-grade corporate bonds averaged=
 just $3.3 billion this year through April 13, according to=C2=A0data from=
=C2=A0the Federal Reserve Bank of New York. These figures have broadly been=
 falling for years, but 2022 levels are nearly 50% below the 2015-2021 aver=
age. ...The impact of low inventories has been clear: In March, Asian inves=
tors sought to buy more than $1 billion of bonds overnight, and dealers did=
n=E2=80=99t have enough securities on their books to handle the demand, acc=
ording to=C2=A0Matt Brill, head of North American investment grade and seni=
or portfolio manager at Invesco Ltd. That pushed risk premiums on high-grad=
e corporate bonds about 10 basis points, or 0.1 percentage point, tighter i=
n one day last month, he said, an unusually sharp move in a market where fo=
r much of last year, spreads moved 1 or 2 basis points a day.=C2=A0=E2=80=
=9CWe=E2=80=99re seeing moves like that, that didn=E2=80=99t historically h=
appen, where dealers would have had the balance sheet to supply the bonds,=
=E2=80=9D Brill said.=C2=A0Now, though, if you want to buy a lot of bonds, =
the price of the bonds will go up. I have missed bond market liquidity.
