      Things happen
   =20
 =20
Banks Accused of =E2=80=98Woke,=E2=80=99 Marxist Agendas as  MAGA Comes to =
Annual Meetings. On the hunt for oligarchs in the =E2=80=98wild west=E2=80=
=99 of corporate intelligence. The Permian Basin Oil Field Is Running Out o=
f Workers, Materials=E2=80=94and Cash. Bitcoin Is Declared a Legal Currency=
 in  Central African Republic.  Crypto Mortgages Let Homebuyers Keep Bitcoi=
n, Put Down Nothing. Buy Bernie Madoff=E2=80=99s house.=C2=A0If you'd like =
to get=C2=A0Money=C2=A0Stuff=C2=A0in handy email form, right in your inbox,=
 please=C2=A0subscribe at this link. Or you can subscribe to Money Stuff an=
d other great Bloomberg newsletters here. Thanks![1] Meanwhile I suppose So=
larCity shareholders could sue and claim that, due to conflicts of interest=
, they were *underpaid* and their stock was worth way more than $2.6 billio=
n, and Tesla can defend that lawsuit too. That is what =E2=80=9Cconflict of=
 interest=E2=80=9D means![2] I mean, the opinion is 132 pages, and early on=
 Vice Chancellor Slights says: =E2=80=9CAgainst this factual backdrop, the =
plaintiffs=E2=80=99 claims against Elon, and Elon=E2=80=99s defenses, call =
out like a carnival barker, beckoning the Court to explore a wide range of =
interesting and arguably unsettled legal issues, including, among others, t=
he contours and nuances of Delaware=E2=80=99s controlling stockholder law, =
the extent to which personal and business relationships among fiduciaries w=
ill result in disabling conflicts of interest, the appropriate means by whi=
ch a corporation=E2=80=99s board of directors can disable fiduciary conflic=
ts, the applicability and effect of an eleventh-hour =E2=80=98fraud on the =
board=E2=80=99 theory of fiduciary liability, the applicability and effect =
of stockholder ratification of fiduciary conduct as a defense to various br=
each of fiduciary duty claims, the triggers and effects of shifting burdens=
 of proof when litigating claims of fiduciary misconduct under the entire f=
airness standard of review and the interaction between fair process and fai=
r price when reviewing a transaction for entire fairness. To be sure, in an=
swer to the barker=E2=80=99s call, it is tempting to venture into each tent=
 and confront the legal enigmas that await there.=E2=80=9D I am not persona=
lly tempted! But the Elon Musk M&A course will have a lot to talk about.[3]=
 Disclosure, where I used to work. Man I am missing M&A law this month. Not=
 the hours, though.[4] There are a lot of complexities here about whether M=
usk was a =E2=80=9Ccontrolling shareholder,=E2=80=9D which can change the s=
tandard of review, whether the vote of unconflicted shareholders was fully =
informed, etc. You can read the opinion if you want to learn about this stu=
ff, but since the vice chancellor doesn=E2=80=99t resolve those questions i=
t seems silly for us to talk about them. He does cite me =E2=80=94=C2=A0 th=
is column =E2=80=94 in a footnote on page 80 though.[5] I should say that I=
 don=E2=80=99t actually know how true this is.  The reporting is that he di=
d decline to do nonpublic due diligence and so, for instance, did not get t=
o review the board=E2=80=99s projections or its financial advisers=E2=80=99=
 valuation models. But did they hand him a draft of the earnings release be=
fore he signed the agreement? My guess is no, but I have no idea, and if I =
were them I would have; there=E2=80=99s no great reason not to and it just =
seems polite. I suppose the main reason not to do this would be if Musk did=
 not want any nonpublic information *so that he=E2=80=99d be able to trade*=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0like, if they did not come to a deal, he could have dumped =
his stock the next day. That=E2=80=99s a good reason for him to decline to =
see years of financial projections, but an earnings release scheduled for T=
hursday? Meh.[6] It is mentioned in the beginning of Article IV of the merg=
er agreement and in Sections 9.3(b) and 9.6. There is also a Parent Disclos=
ure Letter, containing disclosures from Musk and his entities. It is also i=
mplicitly referred to in the Form 8-K announcing the deal, which says that =
the representations and warranties in the merger agreement =E2=80=9Cshould =
not be treated as categorical statements of fact, but rather as a way of al=
locating the risk to one of the parties if those statements prove to be ina=
ccurate=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cmay have been qualified in the Merger Agreeme=
nt by disclosures that were made to the other party in connection with the =
negotiation of the Merger Agreement.=E2=80=9D That is, if you read the merg=
er agreement closely and thought =E2=80=9Cah, all of Twitter=E2=80=99s prev=
ious SEC filings were correct,=E2=80=9D you would be disappointed, but Twit=
ter warned you not to do that.[7] Obviously lots of private tech company em=
ployees are paid in stock, but the model of =E2=80=9Cwork at a startup for =
options that hopefully become liquid and hugely valuable in a few years whe=
n the company gets big and goes public=E2=80=9D does not work for Musk Twit=
ter. Musk Twitter is already big, so its fast-growing=C2=A0days are probabl=
y behind it, and there is no particular guarantee that Musk will either wor=
k to increase its value or take it public again anytime soon so employees c=
an cash out.=C2=A0
