</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Elon Musk is becoming a leading figure=
 in American mergers and acquisitions. This week he agreed to <a href=3D"ht=
tps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27526522.280605/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3c=
uYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDQtMjYvZWxvbi1nb3QtaGlzLW=
RlYWw_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDQyODIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291c=
mNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwNDI4JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607=
f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe466a135" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsco=
pe" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> buy Twitter Inc.</a>=C2=A0in what =
will probably be the largest leveraged buyout ever done by a guy in his per=
sonal account.=C2=A0In 2018 he spent a week pretending he was going to take=
 Tesla Inc. private, in what was perhaps the largest pretend leveraged buyo=
ut ever done by a public-company chief executive officer, though I am not s=
ure precisely how one would measure that. And yesterday <a href=3D"https://=
link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27526522.280605/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb=
21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDQtMjcvdGVzbGEtcy1tdXNrLWRlZmVhdHMt=
aW52ZXN0b3ItY2xhaW1zLXNvbGFyY2l0eS1kZWFsLXdhcy1pbXByb3Blcj9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNDI=
4MjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG=
1fdGVybT0yMjA0MjgmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB=
a8385ed5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgro=
und-color: #ccc;"> he won</a> an important Delaware Chancery Court case ove=
r his 2016 purchase of SolarCity Corp. Future law students will take course=
s in Elon Musk M&amp;A,=C2=A0just like future finance students will take co=
urses in the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27526=
522.280605/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEt=
MDItMTAvZWxvbi1tdXNrLXR3ZWV0cy1ncmVhdC1uZXdzLWZvci1iaXRjb2luLWJhZC1uZXdzLWZ=
vci1lY29uLW1ham9ycz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNDI4MjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYW=
lsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjA0MjgmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vb=
mV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd2393014" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsc=
ope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Elon Markets Hypothe=
sis</a>. Everywhere he goes, he creates=C2=A0issues.</p><p style=3D"margin:=
 16px 0;">The SolarCity deal was=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>a leveraged buyout;=
 Musk did not buy it for his personal account. Instead, Tesla bought it, fo=
r about $2.6 billion of stock. That=E2=80=99s the problem. SolarCity was a =
public solar company; Musk was the chairman of its board of directors and i=
ts largest shareholder, and it had been founded by his cousins. Tesla is=C2=
=A0a public company that makes electric cars (and now owns SolarCity); Musk=
 was at the time its chairman and chief executive officer and owned 22% of =
its stock. (He is now its =E2=80=9CTechnoking=E2=80=9D and owns somewhat le=
ss of the stock.) Musk decided that Tesla should buy SolarCity. Tesla, a co=
mpany he ran, then bought SolarCity, a company that he owned a lot of.=C2=
=A0This raises an obvious conflict of interest, so some Tesla shareholders =
sued. From Vice Chancellor Joseph Slights=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link=
.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27526522.280605/aHR0cHM6Ly9jb3VydHMuZGVsY=
XdhcmUuZ292L09waW5pb25zL0Rvd25sb2FkLmFzcHg_aWQ9MzMyMjkw/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cB46b06364" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_b=
lank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;">opinion yesterday</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">According to the plaintiffs, as Tesla=E2=80=99s controlling=
 stockholder, Elon caused Tesla=E2=80=99s servile Board to approve the Acqu=
isition of an insolvent SolarCity at a patently unfair price, following a h=
ighly flawed process, in order to bail out his (and other family members=E2=
=80=99) foundering investment in SolarCity. This, say the plaintiffs, was a=
 clear breach of Elon=E2=80=99s fiduciary duty of loyalty.=C2=A0</p></block=
quote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The competing theory is that Musk had a =
=E2=80=9CMaster Plan=E2=80=9D for Tesla, that the Master Plan was not about=
 making electric cars but about how to =E2=80=9Caccelerate the world=E2=80=
=99s transition to sustainable energy,=E2=80=9D that SolarCity fit perfectl=
y into this plan, that Musk wanted Tesla to buy SolarCity because that was =
the right strategic decision for Tesla, and that the price Tesla paid was f=
air.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">These are hard theories to adjudicate.=
 Elon Musk is very smart and Tesla=E2=80=99s stock has gone up a lot, so it=
 seems silly to assume that he did=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>have a genuine st=
rategic vision for Tesla or that SolarCity wasn=E2=80=99t part of it. On th=
e other hand, SolarCity absolutely was founded by his cousins and he absolu=
tely did own a lot of its stock, so it seems silly to say that he wasn=E2=
=80=99t conflicted in telling Tesla to buy SolarCity.</p><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">Broadly speaking there are two ways to address this problem. One=
 is that each board of directors =E2=80=94=C2=A0at Tesla and SolarCity =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0can set up a special committee of independent directors to revi=
ew the transaction and decide if it is fair for their companies, free from =
any influence from Musk or other conflicted directors, and then put in plac=
e other safeguards =E2=80=94=C2=A0market checks, fairness opinions, majorit=
y-of-the-minority shareholder votes, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0to make sure that =
the deal both looks and is fair.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other =
way to address the problem is to punt it to a judge. Aggrieved shareholders=
 can sue and say =E2=80=9CTesla should not have bought SolarCity, and certa=
inly should not have paid $2.6 billion, so Elon Musk should have to pay sha=
reholders back,=E2=80=9D and they can make their case for why SolarCity was=
 a bad strategic fit and not worth $2.6 billion. And Musk can make his case=
 for why it was a good strategic fit and worth way more than $2.6 billion.[=
1] And the judge can listen to both sides and decide who is right.</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The first approach is obviously preferable, and it =
is what basically every public company, in situations like this, aims for. =
Oversimplifying mightily,[2] the way Delaware M&amp;A law generally works i=
s that if you get the process stuff right =E2=80=94=C2=A0if you have the ri=
ght combination of independent special committees and ratifying shareholder=
 votes and careful free unconflicted negotiations =E2=80=94=C2=A0the court =
will not second-guess the deal=E2=80=99s price or strategic logic; a proper=
ly done deal will be subject to deferential =E2=80=9Cbusiness judgment=E2=
=80=9D review. If you get the process stuff wrong, you get =E2=80=9Centire =
fairness=E2=80=9D review, meaning that the court gets to decide if the pric=
e was fair.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The right way to do the process=
 is to set up a special committee of Tesla directors with no ties of person=
al loyalty to Musk, let them meet regularly without the conflicted board me=
mbers (like Musk, or his brother Kimbal), give them free rein to hire finan=
cial and legal advisers and negotiate the deal, and give them an=C2=A0absol=
ute right to reject a deal<em> </em>with no repercussions. If they accept a=
 deal under those conditions, it=E2=80=99s probably=C2=A0fair. It is a litt=
le hard to imagine this working with Elon Musk! You have to kick him out of=
 his own board meetings, and you have to keep open the possibility of sayin=
g no to something he really wants.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still, t=
he Tesla board did okay. Musk proposed buying SolarCity several times, and =
the board said no a few times because Tesla had other things on its plate. =
Eventually it agreed to consider a deal and hired financial and legal advis=
ers (Evercore and Wachtell, Lipton, Rosen &amp; Katz[3]) to vet it; it also=
=C2=A0<em>sort of=C2=A0</em>kicked Musk out of the meetings:</p><blockquote=
><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Once the Tesla Board decided it would pursue =
an acquisition of SolarCity, following discussions with counsel, it was det=
ermined that Elon and [<em>Tesla and SolarCity director Antonio</em>] Graci=
as should be recused from any vote relating to the transaction given, among=
 other conflicts, their roles on the SolarCity Board.=C2=A0But the Tesla Bo=
ard believed that Elon and Gracias=E2=80=99 perspectives regarding the sola=
r industry and SolarCity,=C2=A0in particular, would be helpful, so it was a=
greed that the two could participate in certain high-level strategic discus=
sions regarding the Acquisition.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">Evercore presented its analysis of=C2=A0the potential deal to the board =
and recommended a price of roughly $25 to $27 per share; Musk, who=C2=A0<em=
>of course was at this meeting</em>, proposed $28.50. The board approved an=
 initial offer at a range between those prices, and despite Musk=E2=80=99s =
request that Tesla also give SolarCity a bridge loan until the deal closed =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0SolarCity=E2=80=99s finances were in rough shape =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0the board said no.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Then they negotiat=
ed a deal, and =E2=80=9CEvercore=E2=80=99s 10-member team spent thousands o=
f hours reviewing SolarCity=E2=80=99s financial condition, conducting valua=
tion analyses and negotiating with Lazard,=E2=80=9D SolarCity=E2=80=99s ban=
kers. With SolarCity=C2=A0running out of cash, =E2=80=9CElon arranged daily=
 meetings with the Evercore team to push along the pace of due diligence=E2=
=80=9D and hurry up the deal. =E2=80=9CGiven the information discovered in =
diligence, Evercore decided to recommend that Tesla lower its offer,=E2=80=
=9D and presented this recommendation at a board meeting that=C2=A0<em>of c=
ourse Musk attended</em>. (He agreed to lower the price.) Eventually they s=
igned a deal, and Evercore gave a fairness opinion saying that the price wa=
s fair to Tesla. (Meanwhile=C2=A0SolarCity=E2=80=99s short-term cash needs =
were met by Musk and his cousins buying $100 million of SolarCity bonds in =
their personal accounts.) Then Tesla went out and got a shareholder vote; t=
he board required that a majority of non-Musk shareholders vote for the dea=
l, and about 85% of them did.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That process =
is, you know, okay. Better to have a special committee, better not to have =
Musk back-channeling with the bankers and <em>attending every important boa=
rd=C2=A0meeting that he was supposedly recused from</em>. Vice Chancellor S=
lights gives it like a B-:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The =
process employed by the Tesla Board to negotiate and ultimately recommend t=
he Acquisition was far from perfect. Elon was more involved in the process =
than a conflicted fiduciary should be. And conflicts among other Tesla Boar=
d members were not completely neutralized. With that said, the Tesla Board =
meaningfully vetted the Acquisition, and Elon did not stand in its way.</p>=
</blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That seems right. Musk was involv=
ed, but the board seems to have taken its job seriously and tried to negoti=
ate a fair deal.=C2=A0Still, the judge more or less gives up on answering t=
he question of whether this process was=C2=A0<em>enough</em>, and instead d=
ecides to =E2=80=9Cskip to entire fairness.=E2=80=9D[4] Assuming that the p=
rocess was=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>good enough, then the way shareholders ar=
e protected from conflicts of interest is by going to court and persuading =
a judge that Tesla should not have bought SolarCity, or that it overpaid.=
=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But he was not persuaded:</p><blockq=
uote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The preponderance of the evidence reveals=
 that Tesla paid a fair price=E2=80=94SolarCity was, at a minimum, worth wh=
at Tesla paid for it, and the Acquisition otherwise was highly beneficial t=
o Tesla. Indeed, the Acquisition marked a vital step forward for a company =
that had for years made clear to the market=C2=A0and its stockholders that =
it intended to expand from an electric car manufacturer to an alternative e=
nergy company. The Court=E2=80=99s verdict, therefore, is for the defense.<=
/p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">He goes through the arguments =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0about SolarCity=E2=80=99s market valuation, its cash flows, =
its alleged insolvency, potential synergies, the value of Evercore=E2=80=99=
s fairness opinion, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0but ultimately he seems most persua=
ded by a general sense=C2=A0that Elon Musk is a business genius and Tesla=
=E2=80=99s stock has gone up a ton since this deal:</p><blockquote><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">While the synergistic effects of the Acquisition are s=
till unfolding, the astronomic rise in Tesla=E2=80=99s stock price post-Acq=
uisition is noteworthy. Although the relevant inquiry in an entire fairness=
 analysis is whether the acquisition target was worth the price paid when t=
he deal was consummated, hindsight suggests that Elon is right when he asse=
rts that, once valued as a car company, Tesla=C2=A0is now valued as =E2=80=
=9Ca first-of-its-kind, vertically integrated clean energy company.=E2=80=
=9DWhether the Acquisition played a large or small part in Tesla=E2=80=99s =
impressive growth is not clear, but there can be no doubt that the combinat=
ion with SolarCity has allowed Tesla to become what it has for years told t=
he market and its stockholders it strives to be=E2=80=93=E2=80=93an agent o=
f change that will =E2=80=9Caccelerate the world=E2=80=99s transition to su=
stainable energy=E2=80=9D by =E2=80=9Chelp[ing] to expedite the move from a=
 mine-and-burn hydrocarbon economy towards a solar electric economy.=E2=80=
=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But he also says: =E2=80=
=9CI=C2=A0cannot help but observe that Elon (and the rest of the Tesla Boar=
d members) likely could have avoided this expensive and time-consuming liti=
gation had they just adopted more objectively evident procedural protection=
s.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Those are the two sides of Elon=
 Musk, aren=E2=80=99t they? On the one hand he infuriatingly refuses to com=
ply with the basic expectations of law and society; on the other hand Tesla=
=E2=80=99s stock keeps going up. =E2=80=9CElon Musk is a bullshitter who de=
livers,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cl=
ick/27526522.280605/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9iZW5lZGljdGV2YW5zL3N0YXR1cy8=
xMzU4NzYwMzM4NzI0OTc0NTk0P2xhbmc9ZW4/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6c37378e" ite=
mprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"colo=
r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #c=
cc;">Benedict Evans says</a>. He did a deal that was rotten with conflicts =
of interest, and while he=C2=A0<em>could=C2=A0</em>have followed the proper=
 procedures to do the deal right, he=C2=A0<em>didn=E2=80=99t</em>, because =
he is too impetuous and doesn=E2=80=99t really believe in rules or social n=
orms. But also the deal worked out great and confirmed his reputation as a =
business genius. And so the Delaware judge spends some time criticizing him=
 for doing the deal wrong, but his heart isn=E2=80=99t in it. Musk is too m=
uch of a lovable business scamp for any judge to stay mad at him. He does a=
ll the wrong things but they keep working out=C2=A0right.<em> </em></p><tab=
